ther. &#10;Look at America, the rightwing evangelists use homeschooling more than any other group because they dont want their kids learning about stuff like evolution, or being exposed to anything they don't agree with (facts, reality, etc). Situations like that are what make me wary of people choosing it as an option for their kids, and I'm free to voice that opinion. If this was just a talk in the pub I wouldn't be chasing somebody for justification for that choice, but seeing as they've chosen to write a column on the website for a national paper, I don't think it is too much to ask. &#10;-B"/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="901" language="en" documentId="866" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Doomzuk" date="06 November 2009 2:27pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6743132" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="18" thumbsDown="0" origId="866" notes="" title="Ridiculous rules for home schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="313"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="314" end="898"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="899" end="901"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>